    {
      "id": "mem_mqt20y54_ncpe3nga",
      "content": "Commit and push in phases — break work into small, self-contained commits and push each as you go, rather than accumulating everything into one large commit/push at the end.\n\n**Why:** Incremental commits keep `main` (or the branch) continuously in a known-good state, make each change independently reviewable/revertible, and surface integration problems early instead of all at once.\n\n**How to apply:** After each logically-complete unit (one fix, one feature move, one refactor) — build/test it, then `git commit` + `git push` that phase before starting the next. For larger features use a branch + PR per phase (see the established JannieP/rufflo workflow); for small post-merge fixes, commit + push directly to `main` per fix. Don't batch unrelated changes into a single commit.",
      "summary": "auto-memory:commit-push-in-phases.md:commit-push-in-phases",
      "category": "auto-memory",
